{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518095"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:00:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:00:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12874"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12874"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.24,0.03,0.06,0.64]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5316"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38806"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5316"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23151"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1415"},{"type":"tags","id":"2250"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"3233"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4632"},{"type":"tags","id":"5589"},{"type":"tags","id":"5611"},{"type":"tags","id":"5617"},{"type":"tags","id":"5619"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9042"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9623"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38806"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 23-year-old man presents to hospital with severe abdominal pain. A diagnosis of perforated appendicitis is made and the patient booked for an urgent laparoscopic appendicectomy. The patient appears unwell, with a HR of 110/min and temperature 38.5\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. He does not take any medications. His uncle had a complication under anaesthesia but the patient does not recall any details.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe surgery is planned to occur under a general anaesthetic. Propofol and sevoflurane are given at induction followed by rocuronium to establish intubating conditions. An endotracheal tube is inserted without complication. Sevoflurane is continued to maintain anaesthesia, cefazolin is given for surgical prophylaxis and oxycodone for analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFifteen minutes later, prior to the surgeons creating their laparoscopic ports, the anaesthetist notices a progressive derangement in the patients vital signs. There is an increasing tachycardia (170/min), end tidal carbon dioxide (etCO2) (60) and fever (39.5\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC). The patient is noticed to be rigid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following drugs is most likely to be implicated?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cefazolin","Rocuronium","Oxycodone","Propofol","Sevoflurane"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has malignant hyperthermia (MH). Malignant hyperthermia is a genetic disorder resulting in a potentially fatal reaction when a susceptible person is exposed to volatile inhalational anaesthetic agents such as (\u003Cstrong\u003Esevoflurane\u003C/strong\u003E, desflurane, isoflurane) or suxamethonium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMalignant hyperthermia is rare and is caused by an abnormal muscle ryanodine receptor which, when exposed to a triggering agent, causes an uncontrolled rise in myoplasmic calcium. The result is a hypermetabolic state which produces hyperthermia, tachycardia, increased oxygen consumption, hypercarbia (causing tachypnoea and increased etCO2), acidosis, muscle rigidity and rhabdomyolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMalignant hyperthermia can be inherited as an autosomal dominant trait. Genetic testing is available to confirm the diagnosis and prophylactically test family members. The acute treatment of MH involves cessation of the inciting drug and administering dantrolene, which binds and reduces the activity of ryanodine channels. Patients should be hyperventilated and cooled. Other metabolic disturbances should also be managed (e.g. hyperkalaemia, acidosis).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with known or suspected MH requiring general anaesthesia should undergo a \u0022non-triggering\u0022 anaesthetic which uses agents such as propofol and rocuronium in place of fluranes and suxamethonium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncorrect answers\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECefazolin\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Erocuronium\u003C/strong\u003E are commonly associated with anaphylactic reactions but are not linked to the development of MH. Anaphylaxis may be associated with signs such as hypotension, urticaria, and increased ventilatory pressures. Anaphylaxis would not typically cause rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxycodone\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Epropofol\u003C/strong\u003E are comparatively \u0022non-triggering\u0022 drugs (however, these drugs may rarely anaphylaxis too). Propofol can be associated with propofol infusion syndrome, but the syndrome has different features to MH (progressive bradycardia, metabolic acidosis, rhabdomyolysis, hyperlipidaemia) and typically occurs after a continuous infusion running at a high dose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Malignant hyperthermia is most commonly triggered by inhalational anaesthetics and should be suspected in the patient with fever, tachycardia, rigidity, and increasing etCO2"],"references":["Rosenberg, H., Pollock, N., Schiemann, A. et al. Malignant hyperthermia: a review. Orphanet J Rare Dis 10, 93 (2015). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13023-015-0310-1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23151"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12874"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/23151"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-08-09T14:56:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-08-09T14:56:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5316"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38806"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nu